Year 9 out of 100: It was an honor to attend the future library ceremony surrounded by deeply passionate people there to celebrate a future we long for. Likely none of us there will ever read a word of these books. But the books, the project is just a symbol of a future out of reach for us that is still worth striving to make better, healthier, & more beautiful for future generations. #ad POV: humidity can ü§† you? Sweating is a superpower? You probably know that your body sweats to cool off. You probably do NOT know that sweating is not as good at cooling you down when the air is very humid. This can turn into big trouble when high temperatures and high humidity are combined.  "Lethal humidity" can occur around temperatures of 35c (95f) combined with humidity around 90%+. If you don't have access to another way to get cool, those conditions can lead to big health issues within ~6 hours. The kicker is that, as global temperatures rise, global humidity rises, too. (When bodies of water get warmer, more of that water tends to evaporate into the air, increasing the humidity) There are things that we can do to reduce the rate of climate change. We need to reduce our dependence/usage of burning fossil fuels, for example by reducing subsidies for fossil fuel-based industries and by incentivizing greener energies. Although personal choices contribute to the overall picture of climate change, we really need to change the decisions from the largest corporate entities. This can be done through regulatory action, but that will only happen once enough people are DEMANDING action from their elected representatives. Please help spread this information to other people. This is important for the eventual fate of our species. (And having the billionaires escape to another planet does not strike me as a very good solution.) [Note on hunting: There are some peoples today who are thought to still sometimes use "persistence hunting" to hunt prey, taking advantage of humans' ability to sweat and dissipate heat. Some of our ancestors may have occasionally used this method of hunting, along with other more common methods, including the use of tools. It is debated as common of a method of hunting it was for our ancestors, but it appears that it was used at least occasionally by various peoples through history] Embrace your sweatiness - it may be a lifesaver! #pushforpositivepower #science #healthy #medicine #climatechange #environment #environmentalism #lethalhumidity #todayilearned #til

Although chimpanzees are mainly vegetarians, they hunt live prey with spine chilling efficiency. In the forests of West Africa, groups of half dozen adult males hunt together at least once a week, often targeting colobus monkeys. The hunt is well planned with each chimpanzee playing a role, the youngest usher monkeys into the trap set by others. Flankers on either side funnel them into the KILLING ZONE and ensure they cannot escape. The oldest goes ahead where he can ambush prey moving towards him. The chimpanzees take up position on the ground in silence. The youngest of the gang race up the trees and begin the chase. The colobus flee, heading straight for the ambush ahead. Then at the right moment, the oldest chimpanzee shows himself and the monkeys, realising they are trapped, panic. During this moment of panic the chimpanzees grab their prey. Announcing their victory with blood curdling shrieks. The highest ranking male then tear apart the monkey and evenly distributed the flesh. #hunt #chimpanzee #animal #noblenature #creepyfacts #scary #nature #animalfact #animalfacts #monkey #colobusmonkey #flesh #wakeup #touchgrass #getoutside #fact #explore #animalkingdom #fyp #environment #davidattenborough #ourplant #climatechange #offgrid #intothewild #wildlife #interesting #ecology #environmentalist #ecology #ecologist #naturalist

The Liter of Light project, initiated by the My Shelter Foundation in the Philippines, provides an innovative and cost-effective solution to the electricity crisis in low-income communities by using sunlight-powered "bulbs" made from discarded plastic bottles. These bulbs are created by filling plastic bottles with a solution of water and bleach, which are then installed into holes cut in the corrugated iron roofs of shanty town homes. The bleach prevents algae growth, while the water refracts sunlight, producing an illumination equivalent to a 55-watt bulb during daylight hours. Hampir seminggu terakhir pasti banyak yang ngeluh ‚Äúkok panas banget ya‚Äù. Ternyata hal ini dikarenakan perubahan cuaca cukup ekstrem yang dinamakan Heat Wave.  Melansir The Straits Times, Minggu (23/4/2023), ahli meteorologi AccuWeather, Jason Nicholls menyampaikan pemanasan yang disebabkan manusia membuat gelombang panas bertahan lebih lama dan pada intensitas yang lebih tinggi. Akun resmi @infobmkg melaporkan bahwa Bangladesh menjadi daerah terpanas di Asia dengan suhu maksimum harian mencapai 51,2 derajat celcius pada 17 April 2023.  Akibat gelombang panas yang terjadi di beberapa negara di Asia salah satunya India, membuat jalan aspal meleleh. Jalanan aspal meleleh mengakibatkan banyak kendaraan terjebak di atas jalan aspal yang mencair. Tidak hanya itu, pengguna kendaraan roda dua juga berusaha melepas sepatu yang sudah menempel. Stink bugs!  These critters have been alarmingly increasing in number throughout BC. The rise of these bugs can be seen as a side effect of climate change, as climate change has altered their environment. As an invasive species not native to BC, these bugs can have devastating effects on our agricultural sector. They can also be a nuisance to homeowners.  The Government of British Columbia has published a Brown Marmorated Stink Bug (BMSB) Pest Alert, alerting residents to be cautious of this pest in their area. The government is asking residents to be careful in not moving these pests from one place to another as they are an invasive species. Happy #indigenouspeoplesday ! When I drew this comic 3 years ago I had NO idea how far it would reach. I got a wild amount of vile colonial tantrums in the comments, but also a lot of love, and asking for more ‚ô•Ô∏è However, the goal of this comic was to inspire people to do your OWN research on indigenous history. To question everything we have been taught, and everything that has been pointedly left out. This erasure, this ‚Äúforgetting‚Äù, of history is not just of the past‚Ä¶ it is happening now: - Across so-called Canada, the US, and US-occupied islands, native women are unalived at 10-12x the rate of non-native people, and are the most likely to go missing without being searched for by the law. #mmiw #searchthelandfills  - Native reservations have the highest rates of poverty in the US, with over HALF of tribal homes with no access to clean water (with more joining this list by the year) - Native people are 6-10x more likely to be unhoused than the rest of the population, and native teens suffer unaliving onesself rates higher than any other demographic. This list of modern day geno c1de goes on (thank you for compiling @theindigenousanarchist ‚Ä¶) and yet take a look at those environmental stats üëÄ !! Native people manage to do SO much for the planet as a whole, thanklessly, and with all this stacked against them. Don‚Äôt even let me start on the fight in south america. Could you imagine if there was help? #landback is resistance to geno c1de, and it is the key to saving our warming earth. So look into it and the other hashtags. Because a cartoon goose isn‚Äôt a subsitute for a real education.  All love to my grandparents, who kept a map of turtle island with its tribal territories on their wall always. Who passed on their Tsalagi & Saponi heritage to me. Love and solidarity always. Saudi Arabia Blocking Climate Change Deal #usa #climatechange  Saudi Arabia is allegedly trying to block a global deal to fight Climate Change at the UN. In the deal, countries are wanting to call for a phasing out of fossil fuels in order to combat climate change. Saudi flat out opposes this, and has allegedly been skillful at blocking discussions and delaying talks. All 198 nations at the UN have to agree to a climate deal in order for it to take effect. Other countries are trying to shape the deal. The U.S. wants caveats in the fossil fuel phaseout language while China and India are opposing language that would single out coal. Iran and Russia are seeking protection for natural gas. While Iraq has said that ending gas and oil could devastate countries that rely on them for income and are asking that the deal include more aid from wealthier countries. But Saudi Arabia stands alone in their opposition. Even their neighbor, the UAE, who is also a major oil producer, has taken the stance that transitioning away from fossil fuels is essential. This split can be explained by the UAE making a great effort to be a global destination and to have an economy that is multifaceted while Saudi has struggled to produce an economy beyond oil.

Why are all the places I love on fire?  I‚Äôve been grappling with this lately. While I am not directly impacted by the fires in Jasper, the North Cascades, or elsewhere, I‚Äôm left with concerns about our future. . When I first hit the road in 2021, I fell in love with the North Cascades. I spent every moment I could exploring out here, even just to hike into a cloud to see nothing; I still loved it.  . The North Cascades was where I saw my first mountain goat, and it was my best encounter with this animal ever. It was also where I first hiked a trail and saw backpackers and thought, ‚ÄúWow, that would be cool to do.‚Äù  . When people ask me what my favorite parks are, it always makes the list. It‚Äôs partly for the memories but also because it‚Äôs such a crazy, beautiful, and wild place I‚Äôve been dreaming of returning soon to explore more. In 2021, the East side of the park was closed due to fires, and as of August 11th, there are four active fires in and around the park, with numerous closures. This leaves me to grapple with the question: Is this our future? . We often forget that there‚Äôs a loss in many ways in the wake of these wildfires. It‚Äôs not just the loss of your vacation plans or being unable to do a hike you wanted to do, but the loss of community and economy. These communities outside of parks support us as adventurers and explorers to be there. I do hate to see the devastation and destruction of natural landscapes, and I wonder where these mountain goats are now. But we also need to think of and acknowledge what these losses are like for the people who helped us be able to be there in the first place: the rangers, the shopkeepers, the tour guides, the campground hosts, gas station attendants, and more. The people who live and work here allow me to enjoy this incredible landscape. Thank you. .
